  <div class="resource-body">

    <p>Preparation makes a real difference — for your child's experience on assessment day, and for the quality of information the evaluator is able to gather. Here's what to do before you arrive.</p>

    <h2>How do I prepare my child for an autism assessment?</h2>
    <div class="direct-answer">
      Prepare your child by telling them what to expect in age-appropriate terms, visiting or describing the location beforehand if possible, keeping their routine normal the day before, and bringing familiar comfort items. The goal is calm familiarity, not perfect performance.
    </div>

    <h2>What should I tell my child about the assessment?</h2>
    <p>Be honest and keep it simple. The way you frame it will depend on your child's age and understanding:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Toddlers/preschoolers:</strong> "We're going to visit someone who plays special games with kids. It'll be fun."</li>
      <li><strong>School-age children:</strong> "A specialist wants to learn how you think and what you're good at. There are no right or wrong answers — they just want to understand you better."</li>
      <li><strong>Older children:</strong> You can be more direct about the purpose. Many older kids are curious and want to be involved in understanding themselves.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Avoid presenting it as a test they need to do well on. The evaluator doesn't want a performed version of your child — they want to see how your child naturally interacts and processes the world.</p>

    <h2>What information should I gather before the appointment?</h2>
    <p>Evaluators build their picture from multiple sources. Coming prepared with the following will make the process more thorough:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Developmental history</strong> — when your child first walked, first spoke, first used two-word phrases; any regression in skills</li>
      <li><strong>Previous reports</strong> — speech-language evaluations, occupational therapy assessments, school psychologist reports, IEPs or 504 plans</li>
      <li><strong>Medical records</strong> — relevant diagnoses, medications, hearing and vision test results</li>
      <li><strong>Home observations</strong> — notes or video clips of behaviors that concern you or that you want the evaluator to understand</li>
      <li><strong>Input from teachers</strong> — many clinics send a questionnaire directly to your child's school; follow up to make sure it gets completed</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-label">Video is valuable</span>
      Short clips of your child playing at home, interacting with siblings, or showing behaviors that concern you can be extremely helpful. Children often behave differently in a clinical setting, and videos give the evaluator a window into your child's natural behavior.
    </div>

    <h2>Should I tell the evaluator about my concerns in advance?</h2>
    <p>Yes — absolutely. Write down your specific concerns before the appointment and share them, either via any pre-appointment questionnaire or directly at the start of the intake interview. Evaluators can't know what you haven't told them.</p>
    <p>Don't worry about "biasing" the evaluation by sharing your observations. Good evaluators use standardized tools that are resistant to parental framing — but they also want to understand your child from your perspective.</p>

    <h2>How should I prepare for the day itself?</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Keep the day before and morning as routine as possible — avoid disruptions to sleep and diet</li>
      <li>Bring snacks your child likes, especially if the session is long</li>
      <li>Bring a comfort item (small toy, fidget, blanket) if your child has one</li>
      <li>Arrive a few minutes early to give your child time to acclimate to the new environment</li>
      <li>Tell the evaluator upfront about anything that typically triggers anxiety or dysregulation — they can plan around it</li>
      <li>If your child uses AAC or has a specific communication strategy, make sure the evaluator knows before you arrive</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What if my child doesn't cooperate during the assessment?</h2>
    <div class="direct-answer">
      Evaluators are trained to work with children who are anxious, oppositional, or have difficulty in new settings. If your child is having a hard day, the evaluator may adapt, take breaks, or schedule a follow-up session. One difficult session doesn't ruin the assessment.
    </div>
    <p>It's also worth noting that a child who is anxious, avoidant, or dysregulated during an evaluation is providing the evaluator with real and valid information. You don't need your child to perform well — you need the evaluator to see your child.</p>

